task.summary: Default task
add sr_switch class. sr_switches are created with their dpid as a name and neighbours listed as port:neighbour_dpid
broke simple_disjoint by removing some variables, so added them back
sr all-all to groups are created, no flows created. About to change over to IP networks
IP based forwarding working w/o any sr label Also should install the flow rules when new hosts are learned, seperately to the calculation of the groups (happens when topo changes)
SR labels seem to be working. Using PHP i.e. pop the label 104 before forwarding to 104 (done in FF group, you don't want to pop if forwarding to a backup route)

had an issue with packets coming in and retriggering flow rule calculation, even after flow rules were installed. Turns out these were arp packets. which must go to the controller, but must only retrigger the calculation if they contain new information.
Also in this commit (I think), we ignore messages to mac 33:... since it's some sort of discovery thing that gets flooded if you don't ignore. Should probably create a flow rule to drop it
just committing so I can swap over to main
just committing so I can swap over to main
commit before p-space calculation revamp

moved group calculation to the sr_switch file. Seems to work fine. Flow rule calculation is broken, since it depened on some variables that have been moved to sr_switch. I want to move flow rule installation to sr_switch as well, and only trigger it when a new host is added. Group calculation must only be recalculated when a new switch is added
added debug script
moved extended disjoint from nx to working dir
got extended disjoint working, still looking at what it returns
modified extended disjoint heavily to create calculate_backup.py, which returns the primary path and a link protecting backup path so far

added a new forwarding matrix calculator that gaurentees the path (in the forwarding matrix) is the same from a to b as b to. i.e fw[a][b] = reverse[fw[b][a]]. However this path might not be implemented as stated, since nodes along the path may make other decisions - not sure how to combat this.
Also fixed a indexing glitch in label_stack which caused the p-space search to fail on the fw matrix returned by forwarding.py, as this matrix doesn't contain the path where the source and destination are the same, as the other forwarding matrices do.

installation of backup path bucket appears to be working, but overwrites the existing bucket. will need to either add a bucket or add the buckets at the same time. Also, for USNET the backup stack is one or zero, not higher. So if this is correct, we've got lfa
about to change link_fw key from a tuple (u,v) to [u][v]

ping h1 to h2 was throwing errors because the pop mpls function wasn't working on a 2 label stack - the ethertype variable was incorrectly being set to 0x800 instead of the mpls value. Setting the ethertype for mpls fixed this, and I confirmed with wireshark that 2 labels were attached by s1 on the way to s4, and 1 popped after s4. This then causes issues popping the last tag, as the current setuo doesn't have different rules for popping the last tag (which must go back to IP) or popping the 2nd tag (which must go to mpls).
About to implement a host specific mpls label which the edge node can pop off before sending directly to the host. This should hopefully fix it without adding any extra rules.
Also, there seems to be some issue with backup rules where an LFA is possible - just the output should be different, but h1 to h3 backup path adds an mpls tag for s4 before forwarding to s4 - which causes s4 to not know what to do.

host specific label at the bottom of the stack now implemented as 16xxx, but switch specific labels 15xxx used to route the traffic. So any incoming traffic gets 2 labels. Backup path between h1 and h2 work when s1-s2 is taken down. Still that issue on h1-h3 path

fixed part of the h1-h3 problem by adding a condition in the label_stack method to only add label if it's not the first one in the path. with the current backup.py network it's only running through the scenario p=q, so the p != q scenario is untested as yet, but should be fine. Still an issue with the path from h3 to h1, traffic seems to entering h2 and not leaving

pingall works now for any link failure. ovs drops packets that are forwarded to the input port, so backup rules therefore set the input parameter to 0. Had some issues using start=0 end=1, some switches were still dropping. Changed to [0,31] and it all works now.
node failure appears to work now. not integrated with link failure. node protecting group numbers are the same as link protecting groups, plus 100.
